entry.title: [sync] Report sync-the-feature as fully off for local sync
entry.content:
IsInitialSyncFeatureSetupComplete() doesn't really have reasonable

semantics for local sync (enterprise use-case that doesn't even require

the user to sign in).



Returning true has the risk that callers may assume sync the feature is

enabled, which isn't the case for local sync, e.g. as reported by

SyncService::IsSyncFeatureEnabled() or IsSyncFeatureActive().



Most callers to consume this bit in combination with other conditions

that lead to false for local sync, but there are a bunch of non-trivial

cases in code that may run into behavioral differences, potentially

bugfixes.

This reverts commit 2b4c02961570955e40d85646feb0865bb79fe661.



FUZZING_BUILD_MODE_UNSAFE_FOR_PRODUCTION, introduced in r452783, is the

documented macro to be used by code that should behave differently when

targeting fuzzers. Since r562499, this macro is only defined when when

optimize_for_fuzzing=true is used. In r597184, optimize_for_fuzzing was

made impossible to use on Windows. As a result of all of this,

FUZZING_BUILD_MODE_UNSAFE_FOR_PRODUCTION doesn't work on Windows because

there is no build configuration that results in it being set.



This CL resolves the problem by making

FUZZING_BUILD_MODE_UNSAFE_FOR_PRODUCTION conditional only on

use_fuzzing_engine=true so that it is set for all builds that target

fuzzers.



Fixed: 1483560

entry.title: Revert "[iOS] Re-write account cookie waiting"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 1fc770141dd5cb20dfe79e8d1545597660d8c0a1.



Reason for revert: Still causing flakiness, e.g.:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/ios-simulator-full-configs/49119/overview

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/ios-simulator-full-configs/49120/overview



Original change's description:

> [iOS] Re-write account cookie waiting

>

> This patch is a reland of crrev.com/c/4766696. I believe the patch

> was reverted for flakiness not related to the patch.

> ios-simulator-full-confgs bot was able to run 4 times without issues.

> The original patch is in patchset 1.

>

> No behaviour change for most practical cases. The CL might also be a

> bug fix for some speculative scenarios, more details below.

>

> Context: When accounts.google.com is opened, a bottom sheet is shown

> to offer browser sign in. If the user taps its primary button, the

> sheet waits until the account cookie is populated, then closes itself.

> It might also show an error dialog instead, in case of an auth error or

> timeout.

>

> Before this CL, this was implemented as follows:

> 1. ConsistencyPromoSigninMediator observed the IdentityManager for

> its entire lifetime.

> 2. Upon getting an OnAccountsInCookieUpdated() notification, it

> checked whether a) there was no auth error, b) there was a primary

> account, and c) the cookie jar was non-empty. If all 3 were

> satisfied, it closed the sheet.

>

> This approach has some problems, at least theoretically.

> - In 1, more than one notification might arrive. Or a notification

> might arrive before the user taps the button.

> - In 2, the check is still satisfied if the cookie jar is filled with

> an account different from the one selected by the user in the UI.

>

> This CL:

> - Extracts the waiting logic to a helper class.

> - Checks that cookie jar for the correct account.

>

entry.title: Honor @page orientation when fitting to page size.
entry.content:
If an actual printer is selected (i.e. not PDF), and CSS margins are to

be honored (choosing "default" margins in the print preview UI), @page

sizes are honored, except that everything is scaled down to fit on

paper. Make sure that we honor any implicit or explicit @page

orientation, rather than scaling down a landscape page so much it will

fit in portrait orientation.



This regressed with crrev.com/1195546, since the now-gone

EnsureOrientationMatches() function also played a role when fitting to

page, not just when ignoring page size completely (i.e. non-default

margins + real printer).

entry.title: [IP Protection] Better handle OAuth token error events
entry.content:
This CL addresses two issues:

- Fetching the OAuth token can fail because of transient errors and

permanent errors, and we were treating both of those as permanent.

We now distinguish between the two and handle them more

appropriately.



- For workspace accounts, fetching the OAuth token can encounter

permanent failures because the user needs to log in again, and to

recover from this we need to listen for changes to the refresh

token state instead of just listening for primary account change

events.



Bug: 1480010, 1476891

entry.title: [GridNG] Omit trailing default grid-area and grid shorthand values
entry.content:
Per https://drafts.csswg.org/cssom/#serializing-css-values "If component

values can be omitted or replaced with a shorter representation without

changing the meaning of the value, omit/replace them."



This means that trailing `auto` values can be dropped from

`grid-area` definitions, and `none` can also be dropped from computed

styles for grid shorthands. For this, I determine the end index by

iterating backwards. The same approach was taken for CSSOM and shorthand

computed style, although shorthand skips both `auto` and `none`.



This also updates numerous `fast/` test expectations that were

incorrect. I added a TODO for a follow-up that I'll do next, which is

to omit the second if it's identical to the first.

entry.title: AW docs: clarify instructions for exposing flags
entry.content:
No change to policy. The goal of this CL is not to change the existing

flag policy, but rather to provide clearer guidance based on feedback

we've received and data about how developers actually expose their

flags:



* Provide guidance on autogenerated constants. Developers are still

allowed to use string literals, but data shows the majority of CLs use

constants (only 5/180 flags use strings, the rest use constants).

* Add an optional step for the description, and emphasize this is

optional. Descriptions are also popular (only 10/180 flags don't have

descriptions).

* Remind the developer that any chromium committer can approve changes.

Most folks have figured this out from the OWNERS file, but it doesn't

hurt to clarify.

* Remind the developer that a flag exemption is no longer needed once

the flag is exposed. The goal here is to avoid some unnecessary code

reviews on the internal Finch CL.
